{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16234"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16234"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.22,0.19,0.11,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8925"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8925"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8148"},{"type":"tags","id":"8242"},{"type":"tags","id":"10647"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21398"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a scaly, red, and itchy right nipple. She reports occasional clear discharge from the nipple. She has no breast lumps or pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last screening mammogram was three years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right nipple is erythematous and crusty with erosion of the nipple-areolar complex (Image). There are no palpable breast masses or axillary lymphadenopathy. The left breast is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial infection","Contact dermatitis","Ductal papilloma","Eczema","Paget\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E of the nipple: unilateral eczematous changes of the nipple-areolar complex that have persisted for months. The condition typically affects older women and is associated with underlying breast cancer in more than 90% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of the nipple is characterised by malignant cells (Paget cells) that have migrated from an underlying breast carcinoma to the epidermis of the nipple. The condition requires urgent investigation with mammography and punch biopsy of the nipple changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically have an identifiable trigger, would be more likely to affect both breasts, and would respond to removal of the triggering agent and topical steroids. The chronic, unilateral nature of these changes makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENipple eczema\u003C/strong\u003E is typically bilateral and would be expected to respond to topical treatments. The unilateral nature and persistence of symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial infection\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present more acutely with signs of inflammation and possibly purulent discharge. The chronic nature and appearance of the changes are not consistent with infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bloody nipple discharge and may be associated with a small, palpable retroareolar mass. While nipple discharge is present in this case, the eczematous changes are more consistent with Paget\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising that unilateral nipple changes, particularly in older women, should be considered malignant until proven otherwise. Early recognition and appropriate investigation are essential as the condition is often associated with underlying invasive breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paget\u0027s disease of the nipple presents with unilateral eczematous changes of the nipple-areolar complex and is associated with underlying breast cancer in \u003E90% of cases.","Unilateral nipple changes should be considered malignant until proven otherwise.","Mammography and punch biopsy are essential investigations for suspected Paget\u0027s disease of the nipple."],"references":["Markarian S, Holmes DR. Mammary Paget\u0027s Disease: An Update. Cancers (Basel). 2022 May 13;14(10):2422. doi: 10.3390/cancers14102422. PMID: 35626023; PMCID: PMC9139704.","Ooi PS, Draman N, Yusoff SSM, Zain WZW, Ganasagaran D, Chua HH. Mammary Paget\u0027s Disease of the Nipple: Relatively Common but Still Unknown to Many. Korean J Fam Med. 2019 Jul;40(4):269-272. doi: 10.4082/kjfm.17.0143. Epub 2018 Nov 29. PMID: 30486607; PMCID: PMC6669392.","Chaudary MA, Millis RR, Lane EB, Miller NA. Paget\u0027s disease of the nipple: a ten year review including clinical, pathological, and immunohistochemical findings. Breast Cancer Res Treat. 1986;8(2):139-46. doi: 10.1007/BF01807702. PMID: 2434164.","Sandoval-Leon AC, Drews-Elger K, Gomez-Fernandez CR, Yepes MM, Lippman ME. Paget\u0027s disease of the nipple. Breast Cancer Res Treat. 2013 Aug;141(1):1-12. doi: 10.1007/s10549-013-2661-4. Epub 2013 Aug 9. PMID: 23929251."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16234"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21229"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21229"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uPYkH088Mqv8hSfqXJIB61lfylNfub.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/uPYkH088Mqv8hSfqXJIB61lfylNfub.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":427}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T14:30:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T14:31:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8925"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https: